liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Biden administration wants to ensure safe passage for people out of Gaza, especially for US citizens, White House national security spokesman John Kirby said on Monday. "We still want to see safe passage out and particularly for the several hundred American citizens that we know are in Gaza and want to leave," Kirby said. Kirby said supplies needed to make into the region as soon and as much as possible, whether or not there was an Israeli ground invasion. He added the administration shared concerns humanitarian aid would be diverted for Hamas purposes, but said there was no evidence of it happening. Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: US wants 'safe passage out' of Gaza

children.content: The Biden administration wants to ensure safe passage for people out of Gaza, especially for US citizens, White House national security spokesman John Kirby said on Monday.
"We still want to see safe passage out and particularly for the several hundred American citizens that we know are in Gaza and want to leave," Kirby said.
Kirby said supplies needed to make into the region as soon and as much as possible, whether or not there was an Israeli ground invasion.
He added the administration shared concerns humanitarian aid would be diverted for Hamas purposes, but said there was no evidence of it happening.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Allyson Horn Hamas has released two more hostages across the border into Egypt, into the care of the Red Cross. The Islamic militant group says it released 85-year-old Yocheved Cooper and 79-year-old Nurit Lifshitz for "humanitarian reasons" and Israel has confirmed the women are now in Egypt. Two other hostages were released over the weekend, but 220 others are still being held captive in Gaza. The Red Cross says it facilitated the release of the hostages by transporting them out of Gaza this evening. It said: "Our role as a neutral intermediary between the warring parties makes this work possible. We are ready to visit the remaining hostages and to facilitate any future release. We are glad that these persons will be soon reunited with their families and loved ones."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Hamas releases two more hostages across border

children.content: Hamas has released two more hostages across the border into Egypt, into the care of the Red Cross.
The Islamic militant group says it released 85-year-old Yocheved Cooper and 79-year-old Nurit Lifshitz for "humanitarian reasons" and Israel has confirmed the women are now in Egypt.
Two other hostages were released over the weekend, but 220 others are still being held captive in Gaza.
The Red Cross says it facilitated the release of the hostages by transporting them out of Gaza this evening.

It said: "Our role as a neutral intermediary between the warring parties makes this work possible. We are ready to visit the remaining hostages and to facilitate any future release. We are glad that these persons will be soon reunited with their families and loved ones."
